                        "textAnalysis": "Rationale:\nTiclopidine is an antiplatelet agent that is used to assist in preventing a thrombotic stroke. Ticlopidine is best tolerated when taken with meals. The most common side effects are gastrointestinal (GI) disturbances. Taking ticlopidine with meals tends to lessen those effects. It is not necessary to contact the neurologist or prescribing provider if GI upset occurs. The client would not skip medications. The medication is used to prevent strokes but does not guarantee that a stroke will not occur.\n\nTest-Taking Strategy:\nNote the strategic word, effective, in the question. Focus on the subject, client instructions regarding ticlopidine. Eliminate options 2 and 3 first, knowing that the client would not skip medications and that the medication will not guarantee that a stroke will not occur. Recalling that GI upset can occur with many medications and is lessened if the medications are taken with meals will assist in directing you to the correct option from the remaining choices.\n \n\nClient Needs: Physiological Integrity\nClinical Judgment/Cognitive Skill(s): Evaluate Outcomes\nCognitive Ability: Evaluating\nContent Area: Pharmacology: Cardiovascular: Antiplatelets\nHealth Problem: Adult Health: Neurological: Stroke\nIntegrated Process: Nursing Process/Evaluation\nPriority Concepts: Perfusion, Patient Education\nStrategies: Strategic Words, Subject",
